Chained Model Walkthrough: Syria

Forecasting Syria Data

This is a chain of simple forecast models. The data has been imputed, aggregated by Zone of Control, and log-transformed.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(message = FALSE, warning = FALSE, echo = TRUE)

Stage One: Naive

The model chain begins with a Naive Forecast as the first stage and includes a 12 month test set. The predicted values from the Naive model are fed into the next stage.

  splits <- data_tbl %>% 
    time_series_split(
      assess     = "12 months", 
      cumulative = TRUE
    )
  
  future_tbl <- data_tbl %>%
    dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
    future_frame(.length_out = 12, .bind_data = FALSE)
  
  model_spec <- naive_reg(id = "id", seasonal_period = "1 month") %>%
    set_engine("snaive") %>%
    fit(value ~ date + id, data = testing(splits))
  
  model_tbl <- modeltime_table(
    model_spec
  )
  
  
  calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>%
    modeltime_calibrate(
      new_data = testing(splits), 
      id       = "id"
    )
  naive_preds = predict(model_spec, data_tbl)
  
  preds = cbind(data_tbl,
                naive = naive_preds$.pred) %>%
    dplyr::select(c(naive, date, id, value)) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(id = as.factor(id))
  
  naive_preds = predict(model_spec, future_tbl)
  
  fc_set = cbind(future_tbl,
                 naive = naive_preds$.pred) %>%
    dplyr::select(c(naive, date, id)) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(id = as.factor(id))
  
head(fc_set)

Stage Two: Cubist

The Cubist model takes Naive preds as input and utilizes a few transformation steps: Z-score transformation, addition of month, season, and year as separate variables, and one-hot encoding. The model allows a max of 15 rules (we are keeping the model simple), 5 neighbors, and 20 committee members.

  splits <- preds %>% 
    time_series_split(
      assess     = "12 months", 
      cumulative = TRUE
    )
  
  rec_obj <- recipe(value ~ ., training(splits)) %>%
    step_mutate_at(id, fn = droplevels) %>%
    step_timeseries_signature(date) %>%
    step_rm(date) %>%
    step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
    step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE)
  
  
  model_spec <- cubist_rules(mode = "regression", committees = 20, neighbors = 5, max_rules = 15) %>%
    set_engine("Cubist") 
  
  
  wflw_fit_cubist <- workflow() %>%
    add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
    add_model(model_spec) %>%
    fit(training(splits))
  
  
  model_tbl <- modeltime_table(
    wflw_fit_cubist
  )
  
  ## This is making predictions on the test set and collecting accuracy metrics
  calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>%
    modeltime_calibrate(
      new_data = testing(splits), 
      id       = "id"
    )
  
  test_fc = calib_tbl %>%
    modeltime_forecast(
      new_data    = testing(splits),
      actual_data = preds,
      conf_by_id  =TRUE
    )

Cubist predictions and forecasts (as well as smoothed predictions and forecasts) are bundled with the Naive predictions and forecasts, then passed on as inputs to the XGBoost Model.

Round 2 Predictions

refit_tbl <- calib_tbl %>%
    modeltime_refit(data = preds)
  
  cub_preds = refit_tbl %>%
    modeltime_forecast(
      new_data    = preds,
      actual_data = preds, 
      conf_by_id  =TRUE
    )
  
  cub_preds = cub_preds %>%
    dplyr::select(key = .key, date = .index, value = .value, id) %>%
    tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = key, values_from = value) %>%
    group_by(id) %>% 
    mutate(prediction_smoothed = slider::slide_dbl(prediction, mean, .before = 3, .after = 1)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(value = actual,
                  cub = prediction,
                  cub_smoothed = prediction_smoothed) 
  
  round2_preds = base::merge(cub_preds, preds)
  
  cub_fc = refit_tbl %>%
    modeltime_forecast(
      new_data    = fc_set,
      actual_data = preds, 
      conf_by_id  =TRUE
    )
  
  fc_set_cub = cub_fc %>%
    dplyr::filter(.key != "actual") %>%
    dplyr::filter(!is.na(.value)) %>%
    group_by(id) %>% 
    mutate(prediction = slider::slide_dbl(.value, mean, .before = 2, .after = 1)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(cub = .value) %>%
    dplyr::select(c(cub, cub_smoothed = prediction, date = .index, id))
  
  round2_fc = base::merge(fc_set, fc_set_cub)

Stage Three: XGBoost

The XGBoost model uses the same pre-processing steps as the Cubist model. It has a maximum of 2500 trees, samples 65% at each training iteration, allows a maximum tree-depth of three, a learning rate of 0.07, and stops training if it hasnt seen improvement in 5 rounds.

splits <- round2_preds %>% 
    time_series_split(
      assess     = "12 months", 
      cumulative = TRUE
    )
  
  rec_obj <- recipe(value ~ ., training(splits)) %>%
    step_mutate_at(id, fn = droplevels) %>%
    step_timeseries_signature(date) %>%
    step_rm(date) %>%
    step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
    step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE)
  
  wflw_xgb <- workflow() %>%
    add_model(
      boost_tree("regression",
                 sample_size = 0.65, trees = 2500, learn_rate = 0.07, stop_iter = 5, tree_depth = 3) %>% 
        set_engine("xgboost")) %>%
    add_recipe(rec_obj) %>%
    fit(training(splits))
  
  
  model_tbl <- modeltime_table(
    wflw_xgb
  )
  
  calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>%
    modeltime_calibrate(
      new_data = testing(splits), 
      id       = "id"
    )

XGBoost predictions and forecasts are smoothed, then combined with the Naive and Cubist predictions and fed into the final MARS model.

  refit_tbl <- calib_tbl %>%
    modeltime_refit(data = round2_preds)
  
  xgb_preds = refit_tbl %>%
    modeltime_forecast(
      new_data    = round2_preds,
      actual_data = round2_preds, 
      conf_by_id  =TRUE
    )
  
  xgb_preds = xgb_preds %>%
    dplyr::select(key = .key, date = .index, value = .value, id) %>%
    tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = key, values_from = value) %>%
    dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
    mutate(prediction_smoothed = slider::slide_dbl(prediction, mean, .before = 1, .after = 1)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(value = actual,
                  xgb = prediction,
                  xgb_smoothed = prediction_smoothed)
  
  round3_preds = base::merge(xgb_preds, round2_preds)
  
  xgb_fc = refit_tbl %>%
    modeltime_forecast(
      new_data    = round2_fc,
      actual_data = round2_preds, 
      conf_by_id  =TRUE
    )
  
  fc_set_xgb = xgb_fc %>%
    dplyr::filter(.key != "actual") %>%
    dplyr::filter(!is.na(.value)) %>%
    dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
    mutate(prediction_smoothed = slider::slide_dbl(.value, mean, .before = 1, .after = 1)) %>%
    dplyr::rename(xgb = .value,
                  xgb_smoothed = prediction_smoothed) %>%
    dplyr::select(c(xgb, xgb_smoothed, date = .index, id))
  
  round3_fc = base::merge(round2_fc, fc_set_xgb)

Stage Four: MARS

The MARS model is our final one and utilizes up to 4 terms (input variables retained) and a degree of 3 (The degree is the number of input variables considered by each piecewise linear function.)

splits <- round3_preds %>% 
    time_series_split(
      assess     = "12 months", 
      cumulative = TRUE
    )
  
  model_spec <- mars(mode = "regression", num_terms = 4, prod_degree = 3) %>%
    set_engine("earth")
  
  model_fit <- model_spec %>%
    fit(value ~ id + date + xgb + xgb_smoothed + cub + cub_smoothed, data = training(splits))
  
  model_tbl <- modeltime_table(
    model_fit
  )
  
  calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>%
    modeltime_calibrate(
      new_data = testing(splits), 
      id       = "id"
    )

Model Selection

The best model is chosen for each commodity based on which model minimizes MAE.

 best_fit = round4_preds %>%
    dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
    dplyr::summarize(mars = Metrics::mae(value, mars),
                     mars_smoothed = Metrics::mae(value, mars_smoothed),
                     xgb = Metrics::mae(value, xgb),
                     xgb_smoothed = Metrics::mae(value, xgb_smoothed),
                     cub = Metrics::mae(value, cub),
                     cub_smoothed = Metrics::mae(value, cub_smoothed)) %>%
    tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = c(mars:cub_smoothed), names_to = "mod_name", values_to = "mae") %>%
    group_by(id) %>% 
    slice_min(order_by = mae)

Then, the predictions for the best model are chosen for each commodity based on the lowest MAE on the test set.

  final_preds = round4_preds %>%
    dplyr::select(-naive) %>%
    dplyr::group_by(id) %>%
    tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = c(mars:cub_smoothed),
                        names_to = "model", values_to = "preds") %>%
    base::merge(best_fit, all.x = TRUE) %>%
    dplyr::filter(model == mod_name) %>%
    dplyr::select(-c(model, mod_name, mae)) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(value = exp(value)-1,
                  preds = exp(preds)-1)

  final_preds = final_preds %>%
    dplyr::select(c(id, date, actual = value, predicted = preds)) %>%
